## Business Logic

### 1. Summary of the Account Service

The Account Service is designed to manage user accounts through a RESTful API. It allows for the creation, retrieval, updating, and deletion of account information. The service interacts with both relational and non-relational databases for data storage, ensuring flexibility in data management. Additionally, it integrates with external services to validate account status and employs messaging queues for asynchronous processing. The service is built using Spring Boot and leverages various design patterns for clean architecture, ensuring maintainability and scalability.

---

### 2. Service Overview Table

| **Base Path**             | `/accounts`                                                                                     |
|---------------------------|-------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| **Source Repository**     | [GitHub Repo Link](#) (Update with actual repository link)                                    |
| **Description**           | API for managing user accounts, including the ability to retrieve, create, update, and delete account details. |

---

### 3. Overall API Specification

| **Endpoint**         | **Method** | **Description**                                        | **Authentication** | **Expected Behavior**                                                                 |
|----------------------|------------|--------------------------------------------------------|--------------------|--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------|
| `/accounts`          | GET        | Retrieve a list of all accounts                       | No                 | Returns a list of account objects.                                                   |
| `/accounts`          | POST       | Create a new account                                   | No                 | Creates a new account and returns the created account object.                       |
| `/accounts/{id}`     | GET        | Retrieve account by ID                                 | No                 | Returns the account object for the specified ID. If not found, returns a 404 error. |
| `/accounts/{id}`     | PUT        | Update an existing account                             | No                 | Updates the account with the specified ID and returns the updated account object.    |
| `/accounts/{id}`     | DELETE     | Delete an account by ID                                | No                 | Deletes the account with the specified ID. Returns a 204 status on success.         |

---

### 4. Detailed Endpoint Descriptions

| **Endpoint**         | **Method** | **Summary**                                            | **Request Body**                           | **Responses**                           |
|----------------------|------------|-------------------------------------------------------|-------------------------------------------|----------------------------------------|
| `/accounts`          | GET        | Get all accounts                                      | None                                      | 200 OK - List of accounts              |
| `/accounts`          | POST       | Create a new account                                  | Account object                           | 201 Created - Created account          |
| `/accounts/{id}`     | GET        | Get account by ID                                    | None                                      | 200 OK - Account object, 404 Not Found  |
| `/accounts/{id}`     | PUT        | Update an existing account                            | Account object                           | 200 OK - Updated account, 404 Not Found |
| `/accounts/{id}`     | DELETE     | Delete an account by ID                              | None                                      | 204 No Content, 404 Not Found          |

---

This structured response provides a comprehensive overview of the Account Service, its functionality, and the API specifications, ensuring clarity for developers and stakeholders.

## Plant UML script

Below is a PlantUML sequence diagram script that captures the key interactions, processes, and decision points described in the business logic for the account management system. The script includes all relevant actors, components, and endpoints.

```plantuml
@startuml
actor "End User" as User
actor "Account Manager" as Manager
actor "System Administrator" as Admin
participant "AccountService" as Service
participant "Feign Client" as Feign
participant "PostgreSQL" as Postgres
participant "MongoDB" as Mongo
participant "RabbitMQ" as Rabbit
participant "Kafka" as Kafka
participant "Account Validation Service" as ExternalService

== Account Creation ==
User -> Service : POST /accounts\n(Account object)
activate Service
Service -> Postgres : Check account existence by ID
alt Account Exists
    Service -> User : 400 Bad Request\n(Account already exists)
else Account Does Not Exist
    Service -> ExternalService : Validate account (ID)
    activate ExternalService
    ExternalService --> Service : Validation Result
    deactivate ExternalService
    Service -> Postgres : Save Account
    Service -> Rabbit : Publish account creation message
    Service -> Mongo : Save bank information (if needed)
    Service -> User : 201 Created\n(Account Created)
end
deactivate Service

== Account Retrieval ==
User -> Service : GET /accounts/{id}
activate Service
Service -> Postgres : Retrieve account by ID
alt Account Found
    Service -> Feign : Check account status
    activate Feign
    Feign --> Service : Account Status
    deactivate Feign
    Service -> Kafka : Publish account number
    Service -> User : 200 OK\n(Account Details)
else Account Not Found
    Service -> User : 404 Not Found\n(Account does not exist)
end
deactivate Service

== Account Update ==
User -> Service : PUT /accounts/{id}\n(Account object)
activate Service
Service -> Postgres : Check account existence by ID
alt Account Exists
    Service -> Postgres : Update Account
    Service -> Rabbit : Publish account update message
    Service -> User : 200 OK\n(Account Updated)
else Account Not Found
    Service -> User : 404 Not Found\n(Account does not exist)
end
deactivate Service

== Account Deletion ==
User -> Service : DELETE /accounts/{id}
activate Service
Service -> Postgres : Check account existence by ID
alt Account Exists
    Service -> Postgres : Delete Account
    Service -> Rabbit : Publish account deletion message
    Service -> User : 204 No Content\n(Account Deleted)
else Account Not Found
    Service -> User : 404 Not Found\n(Account does not exist)
end
deactivate Service

@enduml
```

### Explanation of the Diagram:
- **Actors**: The diagram includes the End User, Account Manager, and System Administrator, who interact with the AccountService.
- **Components**: The AccountService interacts with PostgreSQL for account data, MongoDB for bank data, RabbitMQ for publishing messages related to account creation, and Kafka for publishing account numbers.
- **Interactions**: Each section of the diagram corresponds to the main operations: account creation, retrieval, update, and deletion.
- **Decision Points**: The diagram highlights critical decision points, such as checking for account existence and validating account status.
- **Response Codes**: The responses include appropriate HTTP status codes for different scenarios (e.g., 201, 400, 404, 204).

This sequence diagram effectively captures the business logic and interactions of the account management system as described.

## API Documentation

# API Documentation

## 1. Retrieve All Accounts

### API Specification
- **Endpoint URL**: `/accounts`
- **HTTP Method**: `GET`
- **Authentication & Authorization Requirements**: None
- **Description of the API Functionality**: Retrieves a list of all accounts in the system.

### Request Parameters

| Parameter | Type   | Required | Constraints |
|-----------|--------|----------|-------------|
| None      |        |          |             |

### Sample Request
```http
GET /accounts HTTP/1.1
Host: api.example.com
```

### Response Parameters

| Field          | Type     | Description                          |
|----------------|----------|--------------------------------------|
| accounts       | Array    | List of account objects              |
| id             | String   | Unique identifier for the account    |
| name           | String   | Name of the account holder           |
| email          | String   | Email associated with the account    |
| accountNumber  | String   | Account number                       |
| accountType    | String   | Type of account (e.g., SAVINGS)     |
| dob            | Date     | Date of birth of the account holder  |
| bankCode       | String   | Code for the associated bank         |

### Sample Response
```json
{
  "accounts": [
    {
      "id": "1",
      "name": "John Doe",
      "email": "john.doe@example.com",
      "accountNumber": "123456789",
      "accountType": "SAVINGS",
      "dob": "1980-01-01",
      "bankCode": "BANK001"
    }
  ]
}
```

### Components Involved
- AccountService
- PostgreSQL Database

### Data Mapping

| Source Entity       | Destination Entity | Key Fields                           | Transformations                  |
|---------------------|--------------------|--------------------------------------|----------------------------------|
| AccountEntity       | AccountDTO         | id, name, email, accountNumber, accountType, dob, bankCode | Mapped to Account DTO            |

### Sample Errors
```json
{
  "error": {
    "code": "404",
    "message": "No accounts found"
  }
}
```

### Root Exception Details

| Name                     | Description                          | Header/Payload | Type   | Mandatory/Optional | Notes                       |
|--------------------------|--------------------------------------|----------------|--------|---------------------|-----------------------------|
| ResourceNotFoundException | No accounts exist in the database   | Payload        | String | Mandatory            | Thrown when no accounts are found. |

### Error Codes

| HTTP Code | Message                  | Description                          |
|-----------|--------------------------|--------------------------------------|
| 404       | Not Found                | No accounts found in the system      |

---

## 2. Create a New Account

### API Specification
- **Endpoint URL**: `/accounts`
- **HTTP Method**: `POST`
- **Authentication & Authorization Requirements**: None
- **Description of the API Functionality**: Creates a new account in the system.

### Request Parameters

| Parameter | Type   | Required | Constraints                     |
|-----------|--------|----------|---------------------------------|
| account   | Object | Yes      | Must include id, name, email, accountNumber, accountType, dob, bankCode |

### Sample Request
```http
POST /accounts HTTP/1.1
Host: api.example.com
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "id": "1",
  "name": "John Doe",
  "email": "john.doe@example.com",
  "accountNumber": "123456789",
  "accountType": "SAVINGS",
  "dob": "1980-01-01",
  "bankCode": "BANK001"
}
```

### Response Parameters

| Field          | Type     | Description                          |
|----------------|----------|--------------------------------------|
| id             | String   | Unique identifier for the account    |
| name           | String   | Name of the account holder           |
| email          | String   | Email associated with the account    |
| accountNumber  | String   | Account number                       |
| accountType    | String   | Type of account (e.g., SAVINGS)     |
| dob            | Date     | Date of birth of the account holder  |
| bankCode       | String   | Code for the associated bank         |

### Sample Response
```json
{
  "id": "1",
  "name": "John Doe",
  "email": "john.doe@example.com",
  "accountNumber": "123456789",
  "accountType": "SAVINGS",
  "dob": "1980-01-01",
  "bankCode": "BANK001"
}
```

### Components Involved
- AccountService
- PostgreSQL Database
- RabbitMQ

### Data Mapping

| Source Entity       | Destination Entity | Key Fields                           | Transformations                  |
|---------------------|--------------------|--------------------------------------|----------------------------------|
| AccountDTO          | AccountEntity      | id, name, email, accountNumber, accountType, dob, bankCode | Mapped to Account Entity         |

### Sample Errors
```json
{
  "error": {
    "code": "400",
    "message": "Account with the same ID already exists"
  }
}
```

### Root Exception Details

| Name                     | Description                          | Header/Payload | Type   | Mandatory/Optional | Notes                       |
|--------------------------|--------------------------------------|----------------|--------|---------------------|-----------------------------|
| BadRequestException       | Invalid request parameters            | Payload        | String | Mandatory            | Thrown when account already exists. |

### Error Codes

| HTTP Code | Message                  | Description                          |
|-----------|--------------------------|--------------------------------------|
| 400       | Bad Request              | Account with the same ID already exists |

|-----------|--------------------------|--------------------------------------|
| 404       | Not Found                | Account not found                     |

## 4. Update an Account

### API Specification
- **Endpoint URL**: `/accounts/{id}`
- **HTTP Method**: `PUT`
- **Authentication & Authorization Requirements**: None
- **Description of the API Functionality**: Updates an existing account in the system.

### Request Parameters

| Parameter | Type   | Required | Constraints                     |
|-----------|--------|----------|---------------------------------|
| id        | String | Yes      | Must be a valid account ID      |
| account   | Object | Yes      | Must include updated fields     |

### Sample Request
```http
PUT /accounts/1 HTTP/1.1
Host: api.example.com
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "name": "John Doe Updated",
  "email": "john.doe.updated@example.com",
  "accountType": "CHECKING"
}
```

### Response Parameters

| accountType    | String   | Type of account (e.g., CHECKING)    |
| dob            | Date     | Date of birth of the account holder  |
| bankCode       | String   | Code for the associated bank         |

### Sample Response
```json
{
  "id": "1",
  "name": "John Doe Updated",
  "email": "john.doe.updated@example.com",
  "accountNumber": "123456789",
  "accountType": "CHECKING",

}
```

### Data Mapping
